  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 6.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "To understand a proverb.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This verse carries on the idea which is stated in ver. 5. The end of the wise and intelligent man's increase in learning and prudence is that he may be thus enabled to understand other proverbs. Schultens, followed by Holden, takes the verb ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "לְהָבִין",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "l'havin",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") as a gerund, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "intelligendo sententias.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " This rendering does not represent the end, but points to the proverbs, etc., as means by which the wise generally attain to learning and prudence. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And the interpretation;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "מְלִיצָה",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "m'litsah",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). It is difficult to determine the exact meaning of this word. By Gesenius it is rendered \"enigma, riddle;\" by Bertheau and Hitzig, \"discourse requiring  interpretation:\" by Delitzsch, \"symbol; by Havernick and Keil, \"brilliant and pleasing discourse;\" and by Fuerst, \"figurative and involved discourse.\" By comparing it with the corresponding words, \"dark sayings,\" it may be regarded as designating that which is obscure and involved in meaning; compare ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "σκοτεινὸς",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "λόγος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (LXX.). It only occurs here and in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 2:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", where it is rendered \"taunting proverb.\" The marginal reading is \"an eloquent speech,\" equivalent to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "facundia",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"eloquence.\" Vatablus says that the Hebrews understood it as \"mensuram et pondus verbi.\" ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "The words of the wise;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the utterances of the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "khakhamim",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "חֲכָמִים",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This expression occurs again in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 22:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and also in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Ecclesiastes 9",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ":19 and Ecclesiastes 12:11. In the latter they are described as \"goads and as nails fastened by the ministers of assemblies\" (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "i.e.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"authors of compilations,\" as Mendelssohn), because they cannot fail to make an impression on everybody good or bad. The expression, as used in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Proverbs 22:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", implies that other than Solomonic proverbs are included in this collection. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "And their dark sayings;",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " Hebrew, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "hebrew",
        "text": "וְחִידֹתָם",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "accented",
        "text": "v'khidotham",
        "children": []
